answer:
Recall that the sine of an angle is given by the ratio of the length of the opposite side to the length of the hypotenuse in a right triangle.  Let $r$ be the rate at which runner $A$ is running, in units per second.  Then the rate at which runner $B$ is running is $3r$.  After $t$ seconds, runner $A$ will have traveled $rt$ units from point $O$, and runner $B$ will have traveled $3rt$ units from point $O$.  Let $d(t)$ be the distance, in units, between points $A$ and $B$ after $t$ seconds.  Then by the Pythagorean Theorem, \begin{align*}
d(t) &= \sqrt{(rt)^2 + (3rt)^2} \\
&= \sqrt{rt^2 + 9rt^2} \\
&= \sqrt{10rt^2} \\
&= r\sqrt{10} \cdot t.
\end{align*}The sine of $\angle APB$ is equal to $\frac{OP}{d(t)} = \frac{OP}{r\sqrt{10} \cdot t}.$  As $t$ approaches 0, this ratio approaches $\frac{OP}{r\sqrt{10}}$, so the maximum possible value of $\sin \angle APB$ is $\frac{OP}{r\sqrt{10}}$.

