label("$B$", B, S);
label("$O$", O, S);
label("$P$", P, N);
label("$r$", (A + O)/2, S, fontsize(10));
label("$3r$", (B + O)/2, S, fontsize(10));
label("$d(t)$", (A + B)/2, S, fontsize(10));
label("$\theta$", P + (0.4,-0.25), E, fontsize(10));

dot(P);
[/asy]

From the diagram, we see that $OP = 1$ and $r = 0.4$.  Then $\frac{OP}{r\sqrt{10}} = \frac{1}{0.4\sqrt{10}} = \frac{5}{2\sqrt{10}} = \frac{\sqrt{10}}{4}$.  Since $\sin 45^\circ = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}$ and $\sin 60^\circ = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}$, the maximum possible value of $\angle APB$ is $\boxed{45^\circ}$.

question:
Two runners, $A$ and $B,$ start at a point $O$ on a linear track, and start running in the same direction.  Runner $B$ runs three times as fast as runner $A.$  An observer stands at point $P$ so that $\overline{OP}$ is perpendicular to the track.  Find the maximum of $\angle APB,$ in degrees.

[asy]
unitsize(2 cm);

pair A, B, O, P;

A = (0.4,0);
B = (1.2,0);
O = (0,0);
P = (0,1);

draw((-0.5,0)--(2,0));
draw(O--P);
draw(P--A);
draw(P--B);

label("$A$", A, S);
label("$B$", B, S);
label("$O$", O, S);
label("$P$", P, N);
[/asy]

answer:
Recall that the sine of the angle between two vectors $\mathbf{u}$ and $\mathbf{v}$ is given by

$$\sin \theta = \frac{\|\mathbf{u} \times \mathbf{v}\|}{\|\mathbf{u}\| \|\mathbf{v}\|}.$$Then the maximum of $\theta$ occurs when the sine is maximized, which happens when $\|\mathbf{u} \times \mathbf{v}\|$ is maximized.  Since $\|\mathbf{u}\|$ and $\|\mathbf{v}\|$ are fixed, this occurs when $\mathbf{u}$ and $\mathbf{v}$ are orthogonal.  In other words, $\angle APB$ is maximized when $\overline{PA}$ and $\overline{PB}$ are perpendicular.  This means that triangle $PAB$ is a right triangle with hypotenuse $\overline{AB}.$

[asy]
unitsize(2 cm);

pair A, B, O, P, F;

A = (0.4,0);
B = (1.2,0);
O = (0,0);
P = (0,1);
F = (A + B)/2;

draw((-0.5,0)--(2,0));
draw(O--P);
draw(P--A);
draw(P--B);
draw(P--F,dashed);

label("$A$", A, S);
label("$B$", B, S);
label("$O$", O, S);
label("$P$", P, N);
label("$F$", F, NE);
[/asy]

Now, we can use similar triangles to find the optimal locations of $A$ and $B.$  Triangle $PAO$ is similar to triangle $PFB,$ so we have

$$\frac{PF}{PA} = \frac{PB}{PF}.$$Similarly, triangle $PBO$ is similar to triangle $PFA,$ so we have

$$\frac{PF}{PB} = \frac{PA}{PF}.$$Thus, $PA = PB$ and $PF^2 = PA \cdot PB.$  This means that $PF^2 = PA^2,$ so $PF = PA.$

[asy]
unitsize(2 cm);

pair A, B, O, P, F;

A = (0.4,0);
B = (1.2,0);
O = (0,0);
P = (0,1);
F = (A + B)/2;

draw((-0.5,0)--(2,0));
draw(O--P);
draw(P--A);
draw(P--B);
draw(P--F,dashed);
draw(F--B);

label("$A$", A, S);
label("$B$", B, S);
label("$O$", O, S);
label("$P$", P, N);
label("$F$", F, NE);
label("$M$", (B + F)/2, NE);
[/asy]

In addition, $PF = FM,$ so $PA = FM.$  This means that triangle $PFM$ is isosceles with $PF = FM,$ so $\angle FPM = \angle FMP.$  But $\angle FPM$ is half of $\angle APB,$ so the maximum value of $\angle APB$ is $\boxed{90^\circ}.$

