answer:
The equations $y = ax + c$ and $y = bx + c$ intersect at $x = 0$ and $y = c$, so their point of intersection is $(0,c)$.  Similarly, the equations $y = ax + c$ and $y = bx + d$ intersect at $(0,c)$.  The equations $y = ax + c$ and $y = ax \pm d$ intersect at $x = \pm \frac{d}{a}$ and $y = ax \pm d$.  So, their points of intersection are $\left(\frac{d}{a}, a \cdot \frac{d}{a} + d\right) = \left(\frac{d}{a}, 2d\right)$ and $\left(-\frac{d}{a}, a \cdot \left(-\frac{d}{a}\right) + d\right) = \left(-\frac{d}{a}, 0\right)$.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair trans, orig;
real a, b, c, d;

a = 2;
b = 1;
c = 1;
d = 3;

trans = (-d/a,a*d/c - d);
orig = (0,0);

draw( (orig + (-10,a*trans.x + c)) -- (orig + (10,a*trans.x + c)) );
draw( (orig + (-10,b*trans.x + c)) -- (orig + (10,b*trans.x + c)) );
draw( (orig + (-10,trans.y)) -- (orig + (10,trans.y)) );
draw( (orig + (-10,0)) -- (orig + (10,0)) );

draw( (orig + (-10,a*orig.x + c)) -- (orig + (10,a*orig.x + c)) );
draw( (orig + (-10,b*orig.x + c)) -- (orig + (10,b*orig.x + c)) );
draw( (orig + (-10,orig.y)) -- (orig + (10,orig.y)) );
draw( (orig + (-10,0)) -- (orig + (10,0)) );

dot( (orig.x,orig.y) );
label("$(0,c)$", (orig.x,orig.y), SW, fontsize(10));
dot( (trans.x,trans.y) );
label("$(0,c)$", (trans.x,trans.y), SW, fontsize(10));
dot( (trans.x + d/a,trans.y + 2d) );
label("$(d/a,2d)$", (trans.x + d/a,trans.y + 2d), NE, fontsize(10));
dot( (trans.x - d/a,trans.y) );
label(" $(-d/a,0)$", (trans.x - d/a,trans.y), SW, fontsize(10));

draw( (orig.x + trans.x/2,orig.y + trans.y/2) -- (orig.x + trans.x/2,a*(orig.x + trans.x/2) + c), Arrows(6) );
draw( (orig.x + trans.x/2,orig.y + trans.y/2) -- (orig.x + trans.x/2,b*(orig.x + trans.x/2) + c), Arrows(6) );
draw( (orig.x + trans.x/2,orig.y + trans.y/2) -- (orig.x + trans.x/2,orig.y + trans.y/2 + d), Arrows(6) );
