answer:
Let $x = \angle BAC.$  Then $\angle BDC = 3x,$ and $\angle BDM = 2x.$  Since $\triangle BDM$ is similar to $\triangle BAC,$
$$\frac{BM}{AB} = \frac{DM}{BC} = \frac{BD}{AC}.$$Also, $BM = \frac{AB}{2},$ so $\frac{AB}{2} \cdot \frac{1}{AB} = \frac{1}{2}.$  Furthermore,
$$\frac{11 - 10}{AB} = \frac{1}{AB} = \frac{BD}{AC} = \frac{\sin 3x}{\sin x} = 3 - 4 \sin^2 x,$$so $\sin x = \frac{\sqrt{14}}{7}.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, M;

A = (0,11);
D = (0,1);
B = (-11/2,0);
C = (11/2,0);
M = (B + C)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--M);
draw(B--D--C);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$M$", M, S);
[/asy]

Then
$$\cos x = \sqrt{1 - \sin^2 x} = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{7},$$so $AB = \frac{AM}{\sin x} = \frac{11}{\frac{\sqrt{14}}{7}} = \frac{11 \sqrt{14}}{2}.$  The perimeter of $\triangle ABC$ is $2(AB + AC) = 4 \cdot \frac{11 \sqrt{14}}{2} = \boxed{22 \sqrt{14}}.$

