The direction vector of a line is any vector that is parallel to the line.  Two vectors $\begin{pmatrix} a \\ c \end{pmatrix}$ and $\begin{pmatrix} b \\ d \end{pmatrix}$ are parallel if and only if $ad - bc = 0.$  In other words, one vector is a scalar multiple of the other.

The line passes through the points $(-5,4)$ and $(-1,3)$.  Hence, a direction vector for the line is $\begin{pmatrix} -1 - (-5) \\ 3 - 4 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}.$  We want a vector of the form $\begin{pmatrix} -7 \\ b \end{pmatrix}$ that is a scalar multiple of $\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}.$  Thus, we want
$$\frac{b}{-1} = \frac{-7}{4},$$so $b = \boxed{\frac{7}{4}}.$

