Let $O$ be the center of the octahedron, and let $Q$ be the point on $\overline{OP}$ such that the plane through $Q$ and perpendicular to $\overline{OP}$ intersects an edge of the octahedron at the midpoint of that edge.  Let $s$ be the side length of the octahedron.  Then $PQ = \frac{QO}{\cos \theta}$, where $\theta$ is the angle between $\overline{OP}$ and the plane through $Q$ that is perpendicular to $\overline{OP}$.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair O, P, Q, R, S, T, U, V, W, X;

O = (0,0);
Q = (1,0);
P = (1.2,0.5);
R = (0.8,0.1);
S = (-0.8,0.1);
T = (-0.8,-0.1);
U = (0.8,-0.1);
V = (0.2,0.7);
W = (0.5,-0.4);
X = (0.8,0.7);

draw(O--P,red);
draw(O--Q);
draw(Q--P,red);
draw(O--R);
draw(O--S);
draw(O--T);
draw(O--U);
draw(O--V);
draw(O--W);
draw(O--X);
draw(R--S--T--U--V--W--X--cycle);

label("$O$", O, SW);
label("$P$", P, NE);
label("$Q$", Q, S);
[/asy]

Then $PQ = \frac{QO}{\cos \theta} = \sqrt{PQ^2 - QO^2} = \sqrt{PQ^2 - \left(\frac{OP \sin \theta}{\sin \phi}\right)^2}$, where $\phi$ is the angle between $\overline{OP}$ and the center of a face of the octahedron.

Note that $\sin \phi = \frac{s}{2 \sqrt{2} \cdot \frac{s \sqrt{2}}{2}} = \frac{1}{2}$, so $\phi = 30^\circ$.  Also, $\sin \theta = \frac{\frac{s \sqrt{2}}{2}}{OP} = \frac{s \sqrt{2}}{2OP}$, so $\cos \theta = \frac{OP}{\sqrt{OP^2 + 2s^2}}$.  Then $PQ = \sqrt{OP^2 - \frac{s^2}{2}}$.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

