yaxis(-4,4,Ticks(f, 2.0));

real g(real x) 

{
return -x^2/4;

}
draw(graph(g,-4,4),linewidth(1.5));
[/asy]

We can write $b = -\frac{a^2}{4}$ as $a^2 = -4b.$  Since $a^2 \le 1,$ we have $-4b \le 1,$ or $b \ge -\frac{1}{4}.$  Also, $b \le 1,$ so $-\frac{1}{4} \le b \le 1.$

The graph of $S$ is the region below $y = -\frac{x^2}{4}$ between $x = -2$ and $x = 2.$  This is a parabola with vertex at $(0,0),$ so the area is four times the area between the curve and the $x$-axis from $x = 0$ to $x = 2.$  (Note that the area between the curve and the $x$-axis from $x = -2$ to $x = 0$ is the same as the area between the curve and the $x$-axis from $x = 0$ to $x = 2.$)

The area between the curve and the $x$-axis from $x = 0$ to $x = 2$ is
$$\int_0^2 \left(-\frac{x^2}{4} - 0\right) \, dx = \left. -\frac{x^3}{12} \right|_0^2 = -\frac{2^3}{12} = -\frac{8}{12} = -\frac{2}{3}.$$Thus, the area of the graph of $S$ is $4 \cdot \frac{2}{3} = \boxed{\frac{8}{3}}.$

